{{Infobox Mars crater | image = Argyre MOLA zoom 64.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = Colorized topographic map of Argyre basin and its surroundings, from the [[Mars Orbiter Laser Altimeter|MOLA]] instrument of ''[[Mars Global Surveyor]]''. | name = Argyre | coordinates = {{coord|49.7|S|316.0|E|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | eponym = Legendary island [[Chryse and Argyre|Argyre]] | diameter = {{convert|1800|km|mi|abbr=on}} | depth = {{convert|5.2|km|ft|abbr=on}} }}
'''Argyre Planitia'''<ref name = "USGS_Argyre_Planitia">{{cite web | title = Argyre Planitia | work = Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature | publisher = [[USGS Astrogeology Science Center]] | url = http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/371 | accessdate = 2013-11-29}}</ref> is a plain located within the [[impact basin]] '''Argyre'''{{efn| Officially, Argyre is an albedo feature.<ref name = "USGS_Argyre">{{cite web | title = Argyre | work = Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature | publisher = [[USGS Astrogeology Science Center]] | url = http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/369 | accessdate = 2013-11-29}}</ref>}} in the southern highlands of [[Mars]]. Its name comes from a map produced by [[Giovanni Schiaparelli]] in 1877; it refers to [[Chryse and Argyre|Argyre]], a mythical island of [[silver]] in Greek mythology.
Argyre is centered at {{Coord|49.7|S|316.0|E|globe:Mars}} and lies between 35° and 61° S and 27° and 62° W in the [[Argyre quadrangle]]. The basin is approximately {{convert|1800|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide and drops {{convert|5.2|km|ft|abbr=on}} below the surrounding plains; it is the second deepest impact basin on Mars after [[Hellas Planitia|Hellas]]. The crater [[Galle (Martian crater)|Galle]], located on the east rim of Argyre at {{Coord|51|S|31|W|globe:Mars}}, strongly resembles a [[smiley]] face.
The basin was possibly formed by a giant impact during the [[Late Heavy Bombardment]] of the early [[Solar System]], approximately 3.9 billion years ago, and may be one of the best preserved ancient impact basins from that period. Argyre is surrounded by rugged [[massif]]s which form concentric and radial patterns around the basin. Several mountain ranges are present, including [[Charitum Montes|Charitum]] and [[Nereidum Montes]].<ref name="planetary.brown.edu">'[http://www.planetary.brown.edu/pdfs/2563.pdf Topography and morphology of the Argyre Basin, Mars].' Hiesinger & Head.</ref>
==Past water flows== Four large [[Noachian epoch]] channels lie radial to the basin. Three of these channels ([[Surius Valles]], [[Dzígai Valles]], and [[Palacopas Valles]]) flowed into Argyre from the south and east through the rim mountains. The fourth, [[Uzboi Vallis]], appears to have flowed out from the basin's north rim to the [[Chryse Planitia|Chryse]] region and may have drained a [[lake]] of melting ice within the basin. A smaller outflow channel named [[Nia Valles]] is relatively fresh-looking, and probably formed during the early [[Amazonian epoch|Amazonian]] after the major fluvial and lacustrine episodes had finished.<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-data_query?bibcode=2000LPI....31.2033P&link_type=ARTICLE&db_key=AST&high= Argyre Planitia and the Mars Global Hydrologic Cycle]'. Parker et al.</ref>
The original basin floor is buried with friable, partially deflated layered material that may be lake [[sediment]]. No inner rings are visible; however, isolated massifs within the basin may be remnants of an inner ring.<ref name="planetary.brown.edu"/>
==Past habitability== The impact that formed the Argyre basin probably struck an ice cap or a thick [[permafrost]] layer. Energy from the impact melted the ice and formed a giant lake that eventually sent water to the North. The lakes's volume was equal to that of Earth's Mediterranean Sea. The deepest part of the lake may have taken more than a hundred thousand years to freeze, but with the help of heat from the impact, geothermal heating, and dissolved solutes it may have had liquid water for many millions of years. The basin would have supported a regional environment favorable for the origin and the persistence of [[Life on Mars|life]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Argyre Region as a Prime Target for in situ Astrobiological Exploration of Mars |journal=Astrobiology |date=February 2016 |author=Fairén Alberto G. |author2=Dohm James M. |author3=Rodríguez J. Alexis P.|author4=Uceda Esther R. |author5=Kargel Jeffrey|author6=Soare Richard |author7=Cleaves H. James|author8=Oehler Dorothy |author9=Schulze-Makuch Dirk|author10=Essefi Elhoucine |author11=Banks Maria E.|author12=Komatsu Goro |author13=Fink Wolfgang|author14=Robbins Stuart |author15=Yan Jianguo|author16=Miyamoto Hideaki |author17=Maruyama Shigenori |author18=Baker Victor R. |last-author-amp=yes|volume=16 |issue=2 |pages=143–158 |doi=10.1089/ast.2015.1396 |url=http://online.liebertpub.com/doi/full/10.1089/ast.2015.1396 |format=PDF |accessdate=2016-03-12 |pmid=26836592|bibcode=2016AsBio..16..143F}}</ref> This region shows a great deal of evidence of glacial activity with flow features, crevasse-like fractures, [[drumline]]s, [[esker]]s, [[tarns]], [[aretes]], [[cirques]], horns, U-shaped valleys, and terraces. Because of the shapes of Argyre sinuous ridges, the authors agree with previous publications in that they are [[eskers]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dohm | first1 = J. | last2 = Hare | first2 = T. | last3 = Robbins | first3 = S. | last4 = Williams | first4 = J.-P. | last5 = Soare | first5 = R. | last6 = El-Maarry | first6 = M. | last7 = Conway | first7 = S. | last8 = Buczkowski | first8 = D. | last9 = Kargel | first9 = J. | last10 = Banks | first10 = M. | last11 = Fairén | first11 = A. | last12 = Schulze-Makuch | first12 = D. | last13 = Komatsu | first13 = G. | last14 = Miyamoto | first14 = H. | last15 = Anderson | first15 = R. | last16 = Davila | first16 = A. | last17 = Mahaney | first17 = W. | last18 = Fink | first18 = W. | last19 = Cleaves | first19 = H. | last20 = Yan | first20 = J. | last21 = Hynek | first21 = B. | last22 = Maruyama | first22 = S. | date = 2015 | title = Geological and hydrological histories of the Argyre province, Mars | journal = Icarus | volume = 253 | pages = 66–98 |bibcode = 2015Icar..253...66D |doi = 10.1016/j.icarus.2015.02.017 }}</ref>
Based on morphometrical and geomorphological analysis of the Argyre eskers and their immediate surroundings, it was suggested that they formed beneath an approximately 2&nbsp;km thick, stagnant (i.e., stationary) ice sheet around 3.6 billion years ago. This stagnant body of ice might have resembled a [[Glacier morphology#Piedmont glaciers|Piedmont-style glacier]] comparable to today's [[Malaspina Glacier]] in [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bernhardt | first1 = H. | last2 = Hiesinger | first2 = H. | last3 = Reiss | first3 = D. | last4 = Ivanov | first4 = M. A. | last5 = Erkeling | first5 = G. | date = 2013 | title = Putative eskers and new insights into glacio-fluvial depositional settings in southern Argyre Planitia, Mars | journal = Planetary and Space Science Conference | volume = 85 | pages = 261–278 | doi = 10.1016/j.pss.2013.06.022 | bibcode=2013P&SS...85..261B}}</ref>
