'''Niflhel''' ("Misty [[Hel (location)|Hel]]"; ''Nifel'' meaning ''[[fog]]'') is a location in [[Norse mythology]] which appears in the [[Poetic Edda|eddic poems]] ''[[Vafþrúðnismál]]'' and ''[[Baldrs draumar]]'', and also in [[Snorri Sturluson]]'s ''[[Gylfaginning]]''. According to Snorri Sturluson's work, Niflhel could be interpreted as the lowest level of [[Hel (location)|Hel]], but Niflhel and sometimes Hel are conflated with the concept of [[Niflheim]], a term which originates with Sturluson.
==Prose Edda== ===''Gylfaginning''=== In ''Gylfaginning'' by [[Snorri Sturluson]], [[Gylfi]], the old [[Mythical kings of Sweden|king of Scandinavia]], receives an education in Norse mythology from [[Odin]] himself in the guise of three men. Gylfi learns from Odin (as ''Þriði'') that Odin gave [[Ask and Embla|the first man]] his spirit, and that the spirits of just men will live forever in [[Gimlé]], whereas those of evil men will live forever in Niflhel: {{cquote|"The greatest of all is this: that he made man, and gave him the spirit, which shall live and never perish, though the flesh-frame rot to mould, or burn to ashes; and all men shall live, such as are just in action, and be with himself in the place called [[Gimlé]]. But evil men go to [[Hel (realm)|Hel]] and thence down to the Misty Hel; and that is down in the ninth world."<ref>Section III of ''[[Gylfaginning]]'', in translation by [[Arthur G. Brodeur]] (1916, 1923), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_T1cAAAAMAAJ&q=thence+down+to+the+Misty+Hel#v=snippet&q=thence%20down%20to%20the%20Misty%20Hel&f=false p. 16] at Google Books.</ref>}}
==Poetic Edda== ===''Vafþrúðnismál''=== In ''Vafþrúðnismál'', Odin has wagered his head in a contest of wits with the giant ([[Jötunn|jotun]]) [[Vafþrúðnir]]. Odin asks Vafþrúðnir whether he can tell all the secrets of the gods and giants, and Vafþrúðnir answers that he can do so since he has been to all the [[Norse cosmology|nine worlds]], including Niflhel: {| | :Vafþrúðnir kvað: :43. "Frá jötna rúnum :ok allra goða :ek kann segja satt, :því at hvern hef ek :heim of komit; :níu kom ek heima :fyr Niflhel neðan; :hinig deyja ór helju halir."<ref>''[http://www.heimskringla.no/original/edda/vafthrudnesmal.php Vafþrúðnismál]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'' at Norrøne Tekster og Kvad, Norway.</ref> | :Vafthruthnir spake: :43. "Of the runes of the gods :and the giants' race :The truth indeed can I tell, :(For to every world have I won;) :To nine worlds came I, :to Niflhel beneath, :The home where :dead men dwell."<ref>''[http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/poe/poe05.htm The Ballad of Vafthruthnir]'' in translation by [[Henry Adams Bellows (businessman)|Henry Adams Bellows]] (1936), at Sacred Texts.</ref> | |} ===''Baldrs draumar''=== Though not a part of the [[Codex Regius]], in the poem ''Baldrs draumar'', Odin makes a visit to Niflhel himself in order to enquire about the bad dreams of his son [[Baldr]]: {| | :Upp reis Óðinn, :alda gautr, :ok hann á Sleipni :söðul of lagði; :reið hann niðr þaðan :niflheljar til; :mætti hann hvelpi, :þeim er ór helju kom.<ref>''[http://www.heimskringla.no/original/edda/vegtamskvida.php Baldrs draumar]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'' at Norrøne Tekster og Kvad, Norway.</ref> | :2. Then Othin rose, :the enchanter old, :And the saddle he laid :on Sleipnir's back; :Thence rode he down :to Niflhel deep, :And [[Garmr|the hound]] he met :that came from hell.<ref>''[http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/poe/poe13.htm Baldr's Dreams]'' in translation by [[Henry Adams Bellows (businessman)|Henry Adams Bellows]] (1936), at Sacred Texts.</ref> | |}
