[[File:Enchanted Land.jpg|thumb|''Enchanted Land'', the introductory volume in the series.]] [[File:The King's England Northamptonshire.jpg|thumb|The Northamptonshire volume in the original cover style.]] '''''The King's England''''' is a topographical and historical book series written and edited by [[Arthur Mee]] in 42 volumes. It was said that the series was a modern [[Domesday Book]] and that the compilers had travelled half-a-million miles in order to complete their task. The first, introductory, volume was published in 1936. In 1989, The King's England Press was established to reprint the series.
==Original titles== The first title in the series was the introductory volume, ''Enchanted Land: Half-a-million miles in the King's England'', published by [[Hodder and Stoughton]] in 1936.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishinghistory.com/kings-england-arthur-mee.html |title=The King's England |first=David Paul |last=Wagner |publisher=publishinghistory.com |accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> It was said that the series was a modern Domesday Book and that the compilers had travelled half-a-million miles in order to complete their task. {{columns-list|colwidth=30em| * ''Bedfordshire and Huntingdonshire'' * ''Berkshire'' * ''Buckinghamshire'' * ''Cambridgeshire'' * ''Cheshire'' * ''Cornwall'' * ''Derbyshire'' * ''Devon'' * ''Dorset'' * ''Durham'' * ''Essex'' * ''Gloucestershire'' * ''Hampshire with the Isle of Wight'' * ''Herefordshire'' * ''Hertfordshire: London's Country Neighbour'' * ''Kent'' * ''Lake Counties'' * ''Lancashire'' * ''Leicestershire and Rutland'' * ''Lincolnshire'' * ''London: Heart of the Empire and Wonder of the World'' (1937) * ''Middlesex'' (1940) * ''Monmouthshire'' * ''Norfolk'' * ''Northamptonshire'' * ''Northumberland'' * ''Nottinghamshire'' * ''Oxfordshire'' * ''Shropshire'' * ''Somerset'' * ''Staffordshire'' * ''Suffolk'' * ''Surrey'' * ''Sussex'' * ''Warwickshire'' * ''Wiltshire'' * ''Worcestershire'' * ''Yorkshire – East Riding'' * ''Yorkshire – North Riding'' * ''Yorkshire – West Riding'' }}
==Revised titles== In 1970, the London volume was split into three. Bomb damage during the Second World War, the subsequent post-war reconstruction and alterations to local government boundaries in 1965 all made it difficult to properly treat London in one volume.<ref>"Preface" by Ann Saunders (1972) in ''London North of the Thames''. London: [[Hodder & Stoughton]]. p. ix {{ISBN|0340158743}}</ref> The new volumes, which brought the total to 42, were:
* ''London North of the Thames except the City and Westminster'' (1972) * ''London – The City and Westminster'' * ''London South of the Thames''
==Reprints== In 1989, [[The King's England Press]] was established to reprint the series, "recognising the need for them, both as excellent guidebooks and now with the added dimension as historical documents in their own right."<ref>{{cite web|title=About the company|url=http://www.kingsengland.com/PBCPPlayer.asp?ID=773748|publisher=The King's England Press|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:King's England, The}} [[Category:Series of history books]] [[Category:History books about England]] [[Category:Topography]] [[Category:Series of non-fiction books]] {{Italic title}}
{{England-hist-book-stub}}

The following is a timeline of the [[Yangon#History|history]] of the city of [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]].
{{Dynamic list}}
{{TOC right}}

==Prior to 19th century==
{{History of Burma}}

* 6th century CE - [[Dagon Township|Dagon]] village founded by [[Mon people|Mons]].
* 7th century - Town conquered by King Punnarika of Pegu, renamed "Aramana."{{sfn|Smith|1882}}
* 1413 - Town occupied by Burmans.{{sfn|Smith|1882}}
* 1460 - Palace built by [[Shin Sawbu]].{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1755 - [[Dagon Township|Dagon]] captured by [[Alaungpaya]] and renamed "Yangon."{{sfn|Nwe|1998}}
* 1768 - Earthquake.{{sfn|James|2004}}
* 1790 - Peguans in power.{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1790s - [[British East India Company]] factory in business (approximate date).{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}

==19th century==
* 1823 - Population: 30,000 (estimate).{{sfn|Morse|1823}}
* 1824 - [[First Anglo-Burmese War#Battle of Yangon (May–December 1824)|Battle of Rangoon]].
* 1825 - British in power.{{sfn|Smith|1882}}
* 1827 - British occupation ends per [[Treaty of Yandabo]].{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1841 - [[King Tharrawaddy]] in residence; city wall built.{{sfn|James|2004}}
* 1850 - Fire.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1852
** April: [[Second Anglo-Burmese War]] begins; British in power.{{sfn|Smith|1882}}
** City becomes capital of [[British Burma]].{{sfn|Smith|1882}}
* 1853 - Port of Rangoon established.{{sfn|Spate|1942}}
* 1854 - ''[[The Rangoon Times|Rangoon Chronicle]]'' begins publication.
* 1860 - [[Basic Education High School No. 6 Botataung|St. Paul's English High School]] established.
* 1872
** Population: 98,745.{{sfn|Balfour|1885}}
** Baptist College opens.{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1874 - 31 July: Municipality constituted.{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1876 - City area expanded.{{sfn|Nwe|1998}}
* 1877
** Railway begins operating.{{sfn|Spate|1942}}
** [[Yangon Central Railway Station|Central Railway Station]] built.
* 1878 - [[University of Yangon|Rangoon College]] established.
* 1879 - City "separated from Hathawaddy District."{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1881 - Population: 134,176.<ref name=lipp1893>{{Citation |publisher = [[J. B. Lippincott & Co.|J. B. Lippincott]] |publication-place = Philadelphia |title = Lippincott's Gazetteer of the World |publication-date = 1893 |oclc = 3155661 |chapter=Rangoon |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/lippincottsgazet00thomrich#page/2249/mode/1up }}</ref>
* 1882 - [[Basic Education High School No. 1 Dagon|Methodist Episcopal Girls School]] founded.
* 1883
** [[Inya Lake]] created.
** [[Twante Canal]] opens.
* 1888 - Income tax established.{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1891 - Population: 181,210.<ref name=lipp1893 />
* 1893 - June: Riot.{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1899
** [[Yangon General Hospital|General Hospital]] founded.
** [[Saint Mary's Cathedral, Yangon|Saint Mary's Cathedral]] built.

==20th century==
[[Image:1911 map Rangoon John Murray.png|thumb|right|Map of Rangoon, 1911{{sfn|Murray|1911}}]]
* 1901
** [[Strand Hotel]] opens.
** Population: 234,881.{{sfn|Gazetteer|1908}}
* 1902 - [[Ministers' Building|Secretariat Building]] constructed.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
* 1906 - [[Yangon Zoological Gardens|Victoria Memorial Park and Zoological Gardens]] opens.{{sfn|Murray|1911}}
* 1911 - [[High Court (Burma)|High Court]] building constructed.
* 1912 - [[Gymkhana Ground, Rangoon|Gymkhana Ground]] (cricket) in use.
* 1913 - [[Burma Art Club]] founded (approximate date).
* 1920
** [[Basic Education High School No. 2 Dagon|Myoma National High School]] founded.
** [[Belmond Governor's Residence|Governor's Residence]] built.
* 1921 - City boundaries expanded.{{sfn|Nwe|1998}}
* 1922 - City incorporated.<ref name=UN2003 />
* 1926 - [[Bogyoke Market|Scott's Market]] built.
* 1927
** [[Yangon Technological University|BOC College of Engineering and Mining]] established.
** [[University of Medicine 1, Yangon|Medical school]] building constructed.
* 1930 - [[Rangoon riots (1930)|Race riots in Rangoon]]
* 1931 - Population: 398,967.{{sfn|Spate|1942}}
* 1936 - [[Yangon City Hall]] built.
* 1937 - City becomes capital of Burma.{{sfn|Spate|1942}}
* 1938 - [[Rangoon riots (1938)|Race riots in Rangoon]]
* 1942 - [[Japanese occupation of Burma|Japanese occupation]] begins.
* 1943
** ''Biruma Shinbun'' newspaper begins publication.<ref name=worldcat>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=su%3ARangoon+%28Burma%29+Newspapers.&qt=hot_subject |title= Rangoon (Burma) Newspapers |location=USA |work=WorldCat |publisher=[[Online Computer Library Center]] |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>
** 8 November: Bombing destroys [[Botataung Pagoda]].
** [[U Wisara Monument]] erected.
* 1945 - Japanese occupation ends.
* 1947 - [[Yangon International Airport|Airport]] built.
* 1948 - 4 January: City becomes capital of the independent [[Union of Burma]].
* 1952
** [[National Museum of Myanmar|National Museum of the Union of Burma]] opens.
** [[Kaba Aye Pagoda]] built.
* 1953 - Population: 711,520.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1950_round.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 1955 |year= |publisher=[[Statistical Office of the United Nations]] |location=New York |title=Population of capital city and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 1957 - ''[[Kyemon]]'' newspaper begins publication.
* 1958 - ''[[The Botataung]]'' newspaper begins publication.
* 1960 - Population: 1,284,642.{{sfn|Nwe|1998}}
* 1962
** 7 July - Government [[1962 Rangoon University protests|guns down]] student protesters.
** [[Bogyoke Aung San Museum]] established.
* 1967 - 26 June: "Anti-Chinese riot."<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Routledge |publication-place = New York |editor = Jeffrey Hou |title = Transcultural Cities |publication-date = 2013 |author=Jayde Lin Roberts |chapter=Sin Oh Dan Street Lion Dance Competition |isbn=0415631424 }}</ref>
* 1968 - [[Planetarium (Burma)|Planetarium]] established.
* 1973 - Population: 2,055,365 (approximate).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1970_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1975 |year=1976 |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital city and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=253-279 |quote=Rangoon }}</ref>
* 1974 - Government [[U Thant funeral crisis|guns down]] student protesters following [[U Thant]]'s death
* 1980 - [[Maha Wizaya Pagoda]] built.
* 1983
** 9 October: [[Rangoon bombing|Bombing]] at [[Martyrs' Mausoleum]].
** Population: 2,513,023.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yangoncity.com.mm/maps/index.asp | title=Historical Background | publisher=Yangon City Development Committee | accessdate=29 April 2013 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225003732/http://www.yangoncity.com.mm/maps/index.asp | archivedate=25 February 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>
* 1985 - [[Thuwunna Stadium]] opens.
* 1988
** 8 August: [[8888 Uprising]].
** [[State Law and Order Restoration Council]] headquartered in city.{{sfn|Seekins|2005}}
* 1989 - City renamed "Yangon."<ref name=bbc-timeline>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-12992883 |title=Burma Profile: Timeline |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>
* 1990 - [[Yangon City Development Committee]] established.<ref name=UN2003>{{cite book |title=Cities And Sustainable Development: Lessons And Experiences from Asia And the Pacific |publisher=United Nations Publications |year= 2003 |ISBN=9211203678 }}</ref>
* 1991 - [[National Theatre of Yangon]] opens.
* 1992 - [[Asia World|Asia World Group]] conglomerate headquartered in city.
* 1996 - Myanmar Securities Exchange established.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-17673773 |title=Burma stock exchange planned by Tokyo bourse |date=11 April 2012 |publisher=BBC News }}</ref>
* 1998 - [[Myanmar Motion Picture Museum]] established.

==21st century==
* 2001 - [[Yangon City FM]] radio begins broadcasting.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
* 2005 - November: National capital relocated from Yangon to [[Naypyidaw]].
* 2007
** September: [[2007 Burmese anti-government protests|Anti-government protests]] led by [[Bhikkhu|monks]]; crackdown.<ref name=bbc-timeline />
** [[Yangon International Airport]] terminal built.
* 2008
** 2 May: [[Cyclone Nargis]].
** September: Explosion near City Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/25/world/asia/25iht-26yangon.16481354.html |title=Explosion in Myanmar on anniversary of crackdown |date=25 September 2008 |work=New York Times}}</ref>
* 2009 - [[Yangon United F.C.|Yangon United Football Club]] formed.
* 2010
** 16 April: Bombing near [[Kandawgyi Lake]] during [[Thingyan|Water Festival]]
** Population: 4,348,000.
* 2011 - [[Hla Myint (Brigadier General)|Hla Myint]] becomes mayor.
* 2012 - February: [[Shwedagon Pagoda]] Festival resumes.
* 2013
** January: Marathon held.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2013/01/20131276433964900.html |title= Myanmar hosts first marathon in decades |date=27 January 2013 |publisher= [[Al Jazeera]] }}</ref>
** April: School fire.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2013/04/20134212236684885.html |title= Children killed in Myanmar school fire |date=2 April 2013 |publisher= Al Jazeera }}</ref>
** 13 October: [[October 2013 Myanmar bombings|Bombings]] injure two people.
** 14 October: [[October 2013 Myanmar bombings|Bombing]] injures one tourist.
** December: Some events of [[27th Southeast Asian Games]] take place.
* 2014
** population: 4,575,155 ([[2014 Myanmar Census|2014 census]])

